cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 300 miles south of Miami, Florida (making landfall along the south-central coast of Cuba)
cyclone.trajectory: Turning north and then northwest today, forecast to pass near or over the Florida Keys tonight and move into the southeastern Gulf of Mexico Monday–Tuesday while looping westward away from the Florida peninsula

weather_observation.watch_coast: Florida coast north of Englewood to Anna Maria Island (west-central FL) and several Cuban provinces (watch areas do not include Port Canaveral)
weather_observation.warning_coast: Florida coast from Brevard/Volusia County line southward around the peninsula to Englewood, including Florida Keys and Florida Bay; north-western Bahamas and several Cuban provinces
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Entire south and central Florida peninsula, including both Atlantic and Gulf coasts
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force winds possible (23% chance of ≥34 kt) with gusty squalls Sunday night through Monday
weather_observation.storm_surge: 1–2 ft of surge possible along the east-central Florida coast including Port Canaveral, especially around high tide on Monday
weather_observation.rainfall: 4–6 inches with locally higher amounts possible, leading to flash or urban flooding around the port
weather_observation.other_hazards: Dangerous surf and rip currents; isolated tornado risk in rainbands
